"script": "Look up on a clear day, and the sky glows a brilliant blue. But why blue, and not green, or purple? It comes down to sunlight and air. Sunlight looks white, but it's really every color of the rainbow mixed together. As it streams into our atmosphere, it slams into countless tiny gas molecules. Here's the key: blue light travels in shorter, tighter waves, so it scatters off those molecules far more than red light does. That scattered blue light bounces all across the sky, reaching your eyes from every direction. And at sunset, the light travels through much more air. The blue scatters away, and the warm reds and oranges finally break through. Same sun, same sky, just a longer path through the air.",
